<paragraph id="8BCB5F108D25FFC2FF22F88FFD7CA94E" blockId="4.[219,651,1815,1839]" box="[219,651,1815,1839]" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">
<superScript id="7C01F2588D25FFC2FF22F88FFF15A945" attach="left" box="[219,226,1815,1828]" fontSize="5" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">4</superScript>
See more details in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE522E18D25FFC2FE3FF881FD70A94E" author="Demite, P. R. &amp; Moraes, G. J. de &amp; McMurtry, J. A. &amp; Denmark, H. A. &amp; Castilho, R. de" box="[454,647,1817,1839]" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" refId="ref6819" refString="Demite, P. R., Moraes, G. J. de, McMurtry, J. A., Denmark, H. A. &amp; Castilho, R. de C. 2016. Phytoseiidae Database. http: // www. lea. esalq. usp. br / phytoseiidae /. Last update: September 2016." type="url" year="2016">Demite et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB5F108D24FFC3FF1CFF37FE5EAA4B" blockId="5.[176,1231,175,1706]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Female. Dorsal shield (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FD53FF37FD1FAEAB" box="[682,744,175,202]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, A) elongated, with constrictions at level of R1, weakly sclerotized, with net-like sculpture on posterior part of shield, 6 pairs of small solenostomes (
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FE56FF77FD08AF68" box="[431,767,239,265]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">gd1, gd4, gd5, gd6, gd8, gd9</emphasis>
), 16 pairs of poroids, and 17 pairs of setae acute, thin, short and slightly different in length except elongated Z5. Dorsal setae smooth except S4, S5, Z4, Z5 weakly serrated. Setae Z5 much longer than others, setae S4, S5, Z4 longer than setae on anterior part of shield. Seta j3 reaches to base of seta z2 but not extend out of it Setae z2 and z4 one third of distance to bases of next setae. Seta Z4 longer than distance to solenostome 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FD9EFE17FD67AFC8" box="[615,656,399,425]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">gd9</emphasis>
and equal to distance to base of seta S5. Setae of pair J5 short, one smooth and other with one barb (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FCE8FE37FCB8AFAB" box="[785,847,431,458]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, B). All ventral setae thin, acute, and smooth (seta JV5 included). Sternal shield with 3 pairs of setae (St1–St3) and 2 pairs of lyrifissures; setae St4 placed on separate metasternal platelets with small pore on each (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FF41FD97FF0EAC4B" box="[184,249,527,554]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, C). Genital shield with pair of seta Ge. Narrow transversal sclerotized stria between genital and ventrianal shields. One pair narrow straight-line plates, semi-separate because partly fused with ventrianal shield, posteroparaxially to setae ZV1 (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FBA2FDD7FB6EAC0B" box="[1115,1177,591,618]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, C). Ventrianal shield elongated, wider than genital shield, with convex anterior margin, subtriangular with lateral constrictions feebly marked, finely striated. Ventrianal shield with three pairs of short setae JV1, JV2 and ZV2. Pre-anal solenostomes 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FC36FD37FC00ACA8" box="[975,1015,687,713]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">gv3</emphasis>
very small, round and disposed posteroparaxially of setae JV2 (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FD18FD57FCD4AC8B" box="[737,803,719,746]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, C). Ventrianal shield surrounded by four pairs of setae, ZV1, ZV3, JV4 and JV5, and 4 pairs of small oval platelets on the integument. Chelicerae normal in size. Fixed digit with 9 denticles (2 large distal and 7 smaller in separate medial row), movable digit with 1 tooth (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FC6AFCB7FC22AD2B" box="[915,981,815,842]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">figs 3</figureCitation>
, D 
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FC03FCB7FBF2AD2B" box="[1018,1029,815,842]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[266,1143,474,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[223,1167,435,1738]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Neoseiulus bicaudus (Wainstein). Female:A — dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D —chelicera; E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV; I, genu II (setal abbreviation: ad — antero-dorsal, pd — post-dorsal; al — antero-lateral, pl — post-lateral; av — antero-ventral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454837/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">1</figureCitation>
, D 
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FBD3FCB7FBCDAD2B" box="[1066,1082,815,842]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,640,662]" captionTargetBox="[348,1091,183,596]" captionTargetId="figure-541@3.[329,1099,174,606]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Neoseiulus bicaudus (Wainstein). Male: A — chelicera; B — ventrianal shield." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454841/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">2</figureCitation>
). Metapodal plates elongated, anterior platelet smaller and narrower than posterior platelet (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FB9BFCD7FB57AD0B" box="[1122,1184,847,874]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, E). Infundibulum of spermatheca cup-shaped and thicken-walled, atrium on thickened cervix (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FF1CFC17FED2ADCB" box="[229,293,911,938]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, F). Peritremes long, extending to level of bases of setae j1 (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FBFEFC17FBB0ADCB" box="[1031,1095,911,938]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Posterior part of peritremal shield curved and acuminate (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FCF2FC37FCBAADAB" box="[779,845,943,970]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, G). Leg IV with three smooth acute macrosetae: longest on basitarsus, short on tibia and genu (
<figureCitation id="134F43958D24FFC3FC31FC57FBF0AD8B" box="[968,1031,975,1002]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1143,192,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-90@4.[221,1167,174,1481]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Neoseiulus micmac (Chant et Hansell). Female: A— dorsal shield; B — setae J5; C — fragment of ventral body surface; D 13–14, chelicerae (D — moveable digit; D — fixed digit); E — metapodal plates; F — spermatheca; G — caudal part of peritremal shield; H — fragment of leg IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454845" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">fig. 3</figureCitation>
, H). Macrosetae on other legs absent. Genu II with 7 setae (2 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FD3CFC77FD2CAA68" box="[709,731,1007,1033]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">al</emphasis>
–2 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FCF9FC77FCEAAA68" box="[768,797,1007,1033]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">ad</emphasis>
, 2 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FCB9FC77FCAAAA68" box="[832,861,1007,1033]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">pd</emphasis>
/ 0 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FC72FC68FC51AA68" box="[907,934,1008,1033]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">av</emphasis>
, 0 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FC33FC68FC12AA68" box="[970,997,1008,1033]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">pv</emphasis>
–1 
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FBF0FC77FBE8AA68" box="[1033,1055,1007,1033]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">pl</emphasis>
) (according to original description).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB5F108D24FFC3FF1CFBB7FDB7AA8B" blockId="5.[176,1231,175,1706]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">
Measurements. Length of dorsal shield from j1 to end of shield, Lds 405; width of dorsal shield at R1 level, Wds 188; length of ventrianal shield, Lvas 142; max width of ventrianal shield, Wvas 117; distance between pre-anal solenostomes gv3, Lgv3 43; length of tarsus of leg IV, Ltar IV 113. Length of setae: j1 22, j3 29, j4 12, j5 12, j6 14, J2 14, J5 13, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE4039D78D24FFC3FB4CFB17FF39AAAB" degrees="4" direction="south" minutes="36" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" precision="925" value="-4.6">s4 36</geoCoordinate>
, z2 20, z4 20, z5 12, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE4039D78D24FFC3FE4FFB37FE01AAAB" box="[438,502,1199,1226]" degrees="2" direction="south" minutes="30" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" precision="925" value="-2.5">S2 30</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE4039D78D24FFC3FDF8FB37FDB5AAAB" box="[513,578,1199,1226]" degrees="4" direction="south" minutes="32" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" precision="925" value="-4.5333333">S4 32</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE4039D78D24FFC3FDB4FB37FD7AAAAB" box="[589,653,1199,1226]" degrees="5" direction="south" minutes="36" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" precision="925" value="-5.6">S5 36</geoCoordinate>
, Z1 22, Z4 38, Z5 86, r3 30, R1 25, JV5 61; macrosetae on leg IV: ge 29, ti 27, tar 77.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB5F108D24FFC3FF1CFB77FCEFAB6B" blockId="5.[176,1231,175,1706]" box="[229,792,1263,1290]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">
Male from 
<typeStatus id="54CFE1B28D24FFC3FE91FB77FE6DAB6B" box="[360,410,1263,1290]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">type</typeStatus>
locality of the species unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB5F108D24FFC3FF1CFA97FD96A8CB" blockId="5.[176,1231,175,1706]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">
Study of the 
<typeStatus id="54CFE1B28D24FFC3FE85FA97FE14AB4B" box="[380,483,1295,1322]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FDF2FA88FD7EAB48" authorityName="Chant, Hansell" authorityYear="1971" box="[523,649,1296,1321]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Amblyseius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micmac">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FDF2FA88FD7EAB48" box="[523,649,1296,1321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. micmac</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gave possibility to solve several taxonomic questions in this two mites. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FE2AFAB7FD43AB28" baseAuthorityName="Chant &amp; Hansell" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[467,692,1327,1353]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micmac">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FE2AFAB7FD43AB28" box="[467,692,1327,1353]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">Neoseiulus micmac</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has many characters, which do it similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FF49FAC8FEC9AB08" baseAuthorityName="Wainstein" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[176,318,1359,1385]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicaudus">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FF49FAC8FEC9AB08" box="[176,318,1359,1385]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. bicaudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE522E18D24FFC3FE8DFAD7FDCDAB0B" author="Congdon, B. D." box="[372,570,1359,1386]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" pagination="3 - 27" refId="ref6780" refString="Congdon, B. D. 2002. The family Phytoseiidae (Acari) in western Washington State with descriptions of three new species. International Journal of Acarology, 28 (1), 3 - 27." type="journal article" year="2002">Congdon (2002)</bibRefCitation>
considered it to be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FC1CFAC8FB83AB08" baseAuthorityName="Wainstein" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[997,1140,1359,1385]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicaudus">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FC1CFAC8FB83AB08" box="[997,1140,1359,1385]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. bicaudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE522E18D24FFC3FB7CFAD7FE57ABEB" author="Chant, D. A. &amp; McMurtry, J. A." pageId="5" pageNumber="300" pagination="3 - 46" refId="ref6689" refString="Chant, D. A., McMurtry, J. A. 2003. A review of the subfamily Amblyseiinae Muma. Part I. Neoseiulini new tribe. International Journal of Acarology, 29 (1), 3 - 46." type="journal article" year="2003">Chant &amp; McMurtry (2003)</bibRefCitation>
restored 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FDEAFAE8FD65ABE8" baseAuthorityName="Chant &amp; Hansell" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[531,658,1392,1417]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micmac">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FDEAFAE8FD65ABE8" box="[531,658,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. micmac</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species name, but 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE522E18D24FFC3FC08FAF7FF0BABCB" author="Denmark, D. A. &amp; Evans G. A." pageId="5" pageNumber="300" pagination="1 - 451" refId="ref6882" refString="Denmark, D. A., Evans G. A. 2011. Phytoseiidae of North America and Hawaii (Acari: Mesostigmata). Indira Publishing House, West Bloomfield, 1 - 451." type="book chapter" year="2011">
<collectingCountry id="F3631F808D24FFC3FC08FAF7FB96ABEB" box="[1009,1121,1391,1418]" name="Denmark" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">Denmark</collectingCountry>
&amp; Evans (2011)
</bibRefCitation>
supported Congdon´s opinion. However, detailed comparison of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FBE0FA08FB6EABC8" baseAuthorityName="Chant &amp; Hansell" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[1049,1177,1424,1449]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micmac">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FBE0FA08FB6EABC8" box="[1049,1177,1424,1449]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. micmac</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FF49FA28FECCABA8" baseAuthorityName="Wainstein" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[176,315,1455,1481]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicaudus">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FF49FA28FECCABA8" box="[176,315,1455,1481]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. bicaudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="54CFE1B28D24FFC3FEBAFA37FE42ABAB" box="[323,437,1455,1482]" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">holotypes</typeStatus>
reveals significant differences between them. Actually, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FBBAFA28FB39ABA8" baseAuthorityName="Wainstein" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[1091,1230,1455,1481]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicaudus">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FBBAFA28FB39ABA8" box="[1091,1230,1455,1481]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. bicaudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 7 pairs of dorsal solenostomes (gd2 present), 6 or 7 large teeth on fixed digit of chelicera, smooth J5, and serrated JV5 setae, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FCEBFA68FC65A868" baseAuthorityName="Chant &amp; Hansell" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[786,914,1520,1545]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micmac">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FCEBFA68FC65A868" box="[786,914,1520,1545]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. micmac</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has only 6 pairs of dorsal solenostomes (gd2 absent), 9 teeth (2 distal large teeth and 7 tiny denticles) on Df, seta J5 serrated with 1 jag and seta JV5 smooth. Besides that, infundibulum of spermatheca of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FF49F9C8FEDAA808" baseAuthorityName="Chant &amp; Hansell" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[176,301,1616,1641]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micmac">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FF49F9C8FEDAA808" box="[176,301,1616,1641]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. micmac</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
U-form and thick-walled, whereas infundibulum of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FC57F9C8FBCBA808" baseAuthorityName="Wainstein" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[942,1084,1615,1641]" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicaudus">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FC57F9C8FBCBA808" box="[942,1084,1615,1641]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. bicaudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cup-shaped and thin-walled. Thus, these morphological differences convincingly indicated that 
<taxonomicName id="4C7424938D24FFC3FB80F9E8FF16A8C8" baseAuthorityName="Chant &amp; Hansell" baseAuthorityYear="1971" class="Arachnida" family="Phytoseiidae" genus="Neoseiulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micmac">
<emphasis id="B90083028D24FFC3FB80F9E8FF16A8C8" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="300">N. micmac</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should considered a valid name.
</paragraph>
